{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"a6f5def9-fc03-4503-9f6f-a6c3114ed309","content":"In ASP.NET Core, `AddScoped` creates one instance **per HTTP request** — each request gets a fresh `DbContext`. But in MAUI, there are no HTTP requests. There's only one long-lived \"scope\" (the app itself), so `AddScoped` behaves like `AddSingleton`. Your `DbContext` is created once and reused for the entire app lifetime.\n\n**Fixes:**\n\n1. **Use `AddTransient`** — gives a new `DbContext` per injection:\n   ```csharp\n   builder.Services.AddTransient<MyDbContext>();\n   ```\n\n2. **Use `IDbContextFactory` (recommended)** — explicit control over lifetime:\n   ```csharp\n   builder.Services.AddDbContextFactory<MyDbContext>();\n   ```\n   Then inject and use it:\n   ```csharp\n   public MyPage(IDbContextFactory<MyDbContext> factory)\n   {\n       using var db = factory.CreateDbContext();\n       // db is disposed when you're done\n   }\n   ```\n\nOption 2 is preferred because it makes the `DbContext` lifetime explicit and avoids issues with long-lived tracked entities or stale data.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"fec5d9b2-8582-4ae1-bb29-680df15c53f6","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The user is asking about a common pitfall when transitioning from ASP.NET Core to .NET MAUI regarding dependency injection scoping, specifically with `AddScoped` and `DbContext`. This is a conceptual question I can answer directly without needing to look at any code.\n\nThe key issue: In ASP.NET Core, `AddScoped` creates a new instance per HTTP request. In MAUI, there's no concept of an HTTP request, so `Scoped` behaves essentially the same as `Singleton` — one instance for the entire app lifetime. That's why the DbContext data persists across navigations.","outputTokens":435,"requestId":"044D:75CA6:BDBBD6:D78D4D:6A027BFB"},"id":"dd9ed5ed-d23d-4269-8c4f-8fb728fc16cd","timestamp":"2026-05-12T01:01:57.742Z","parentId":"b07f684b-0269-4152-9f99-b1778fe2eb72"}
